Flights

Datasets

In this notebook we are going to look at a relatively well-known data set of domestic flights leaving from the three major NYC airports in the year 2013. There are a few datasets. First, a dataset of the flights themselves. Note that all of the times are in local time (including arrival hour) and the departure and arrival delays are in seconds.

flights <- read_csv("data/flights.csv")

We also have a data set of the airports. These include the time zone of the airport as well as the location as longitude and latitude. We’ll use a semi join to remove small airports that are not in our collection.

airports <- read_csv("data/airports.csv") %>%
  semi_join(flights, by = c("faa" = "dest"))

I have already removed the fligths to Alaska and Hawaii, so I also removed them above from the state polygons.

Some Exploratory Analysis

As a warm-up, group the data by the destination airport and compute the number of flights to each destination. Arrange the data in descending count.

flights %>%
  group_by(dest) %>%
  summarize(n = n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(n))

Now, create a spatial plot that shows the location of each airport overlaid over the state boundaries. Scale the sizes of the airports relative to the number of flights. Transform the coordinate system to one with crs equal to 5069.

flights %>%
  group_by(dest) %>%
  summarize(n = n()) %>%
  inner_join(airports, by = c("dest" = "faa")) %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("lon", "lat"), crs = 4326, remove = FALSE) %>%
  st_transform(5069) %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_sf(data = state, fill = "white") +
    geom_sf(aes(size = n))

Departure Time

Now, create a column dep_time using the make_datetime function from the departure time variables. Use the function force_tz and the time zone “America/New_York” to tell R that these are in local NYC time rather than UTC. Once you get the answer, store the results in the flights data.

flights <- flights %>%
  mutate(dep_time = make_datetime(year, month, day, dep_hour, dep_min)) %>%
  mutate(dep_time = force_tz(dep_time, tzone = "America/New_York"))

Now, compute the weekday of each flight, group by the weekday, and summarize the percentage of flights on each weekday that are at least 1 hour late departing.

flights %>%
  mutate(wday = wday(dep_time, label = TRUE)) %>%
  group_by(wday) %>%
  summarize(dep_delay = mean(dep_delay > 60 * 60) * 100)
## # A tibble: 7 × 2

Weather

We want to join the flights data to the weather data set, group by the variable visib (the visibility in miles), and compute the percentage of flights that are at least 15 minutes late. Plot the results as a line plot with visib on the x-axis and the percentage on the y-axis.

flights %>%
  mutate(time_hour = floor_date(dep_time, "hour")) %>%
  inner_join(weather, by = c("origin", "time_hour")) %>%
  group_by(visib) %>%
  summarize(mu = mean(dep_delay > 15 * 60) * 100) %>%
  ggplot(aes(visib, mu)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_line()

Repeat the prior question with the wind speed in place of the visibility. (you may want to filter to only include wind speeds under 50 mph.)

flights %>%
  mutate(time_hour = floor_date(dep_time, "hour")) %>%
  inner_join(weather, by = c("origin", "time_hour")) %>%
  group_by(wind_speed) %>%
  filter(wind_speed < 50) %>%
  summarize(mu = mean(dep_delay > 15 * 60) * 100) %>%
  ggplot(aes(wind_speed, mu)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_line()

Arrival Time

We now want to create a column arr_time as we did above. The arrival times are also all local, but are in different time zones. In the code below, join flights to airports, create arr_time and then use the function force_tzs to convert all of the time zones into “America/New_York”.

flights <- flights %>%
  inner_join(airports, by = c("dest" = "faa")) %>%
  mutate(arr_time = make_datetime(year, month, day, arr_hour, arr_min)) %>%
  mutate(arr_time = force_tzs(arr_time, tzones = tzone, tzone_out = "America/New_York"))

Flight Time

Update the flights data by adding 24 * 60 * 60 seconds to any row where the arrival time is less than the departure time. This should fix most of the errors you found above.

flights <- flights %>%
  mutate(arr_time = if_else(arr_time < dep_time, arr_time + 24 * 60 * 60, arr_time))

Take the flights data and compute the difference between the arrival and departure time. Group by the destination and compute the average flight time. Join the data with the airports data and arrange from the longest to the shortest destinations.

flights %>%
  mutate(tdiff = arr_time - dep_time) %>%
  group_by(dest) %>%
  summarize(avg = mean(tdiff)) %>%
  arrange(avg) %>%
  inner_join(airports, by = c("dest" = "faa"))

Take the data you created above and make a spatial plot similar to the first one. However, this time we want to color the points according to the average flight time from NYC. Use the following color scale:

scale_color_distiller(palette = “Spectral”, guide = “legend”, n.breaks = 10)

Take a moment to adjust the plot to make it look nice. Perhaps set pch = 21?

flights %>%
  mutate(tdiff = arr_time - dep_time) %>%
  group_by(dest) %>%
  summarize(avg = as.numeric(mean(tdiff, na.rm = TRUE)) / 60) %>%
  arrange(avg) %>%
  inner_join(airports, by = c("dest" = "faa")) %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("lon", "lat"), crs = 4326, remove = FALSE) %>%
  st_transform(5069) %>%
  filter(avg < 7) %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_sf(data = filter(state, !(abb %in% c("AK", "HI"))), fill = "white", size = 0.3) +
    geom_sf(aes(fill = avg), size = 5, color = "black", pch = 21) +
    scale_fill_distiller(
      palette = "Spectral", guide = "legend", n.breaks = 10
    ) +
    labs(fill = "Mean Flight\n    (Hours)")
